******
[2] Massachusetts
Date: 24 Aug 2018
Source: Mass Live [edited]
https://www.masslive.com/news/index.ssf/2018/08/3_human_cases_of_west_nile_vir.html


A horse infected with the West Nile virus had to be put down, and the 1st 3 cases of the virus in humans in Massachusetts this year [2018] were identified, state officials said Friday [24 Aug 2018].

The horse was stabled in Hampshire County, "became severely ill, and had to be euthanized," a press release from the Massachusetts Department of Public Health said.

A woman in her 70s from Worcester County was hospitalized with symptoms from the virus but has since been discharged, the press release said.

A woman in her 60s from Middlesex County was not hospitalized during her illness, the press release said.

A Suffolk County woman in her 50s was hospitalized but has been discharged, the press release said.

The state limits identifying information about human and animal cases of West Nile virus only to the county where they reside, said Ann Scales, Department of Public Health spokeswoman.

"August and September are the months when we typically see more human cases, because it is the beginning of the peak season for possible West Nile virus human infections," said Dr. Catherine Brown, state epidemiologist.

There are 94 Massachusetts towns and cities where WNV mosquitoes have been found in 2018. Officials have detected mosquitoes carrying West Nile virus in dozens of Massachusetts communities.

"These new human cases illustrate why we informed people about the increased risk for human infections earlier this week," Brown said.

In 2017, there were 6 human cases of WNV infection identified in Massachusetts.

West Nile virus is a mosquito-carried virus that can cause illness ranging from a mild fever to more serious disease like encephalitis or meningitis. It was 1st identified in the United States in 1999.

The world has 3000 species of mosquito, and they transmit more diseases than any other creature, according to National Geographic.

West Nile virus can infect people of all ages, though people over the age of 50 are at higher risk for severe disease. Most people infected with the virus have no symptoms, the press release said.

Virus symptoms tend to include fever and flu-like illness [in people], the press release said.

"There has been an increase in WNV-infected mosquitoes identified this year [2018] throughout the state, an indication that the risk is widespread and ongoing," said Monica Bharel, commissioner with the Massachusetts Department of Public Health.

"That means this year [2018], it is extremely important for people to take steps to avoid mosquito bites, including using repellents, wearing clothing to reduce exposed skin, dumping standing water, and moving indoors when you notice mosquitoes biting you."

The Department of Public Health Tuesday [21 Aug 2018] raised the risk level for West Nile virus to moderate from low in every Massachusetts city and town, the press release said.

Among steps people can take to avoid illnesses from mosquito bites are, said the Department of Public Health:

- to avoid mosquito bites by applying insect repellant when outdoors. Use a repellent with DEET (N, N-diethyl-m-toluamide), permethrin, picaridin (KBR 3023), oil of lemon eucalyptus [p-methane 3, 8-diol (PMD)], or IR3535 according to the instructions on the product label. DEET products should not be used on infants under 2 months of age and should be used in concentrations of 30 percent less on older children. Oil of lemon eucalyptus should not be used on children under 3 years of age;
- to be aware of peak mosquito hours, which are between dusk to dawn. Consider rescheduling outdoor activities;
- to wear long sleeves, long pants, and socks outside to help in blocking mosquitoes from your skin;
- to mosquito-proof your home by draining standing water, which is where mosquitoes lay eggs, fix or install screens;
- to protect horses and other animals by flushing out water troughs at least once a week;
- to keep horses in indoor stalls at night to reduce their risk of exposure to mosquitoes.
For more information, visit http://mass.gov/mosquito-borne-diseases or call 1-617-983-6800.

[Byline: Mike Plaisance

